Putin told Zelensky in the interview that the Ukrainian parliament's decision to hold local elections contradicts the Minsk peace agreement and threatens the prospects for settling the conflict in eastern Ukraine.
Ukraine's parliament ruled last week that the upcoming local elections will not take place in territory controlled by pro-Russian rebels.
The Minsk agreement envisages that Kiev will regain control of Ukraine's separatist-occupied border with Russia after granting these regions broad autonomy and holding local elections.
According to the Unian news agency, Zelenskiy's office said that the two leaders agreed on the benefits of the upcoming ceasefire in Donbass and on the need to implement other measures to promote peace in the region, such as demining combat zones and withdrawing part of the troops from the front.
Zelenskiy also called on Putin to release Ukrainians detained in eastern Ukraine, the occupied Crimean peninsula and Russia itself.
The Minsk agreement has helped stop the fighting, but intermittent firefights and artillery attacks continue to kill people on both sides of the front.
The conflict in Donbass has left more than 14,000 people dead since the spring of 2014.
