Bio LPG has arrived in the Czech Republic, promising ecological operation
Liquefied petroleum gas, abbreviated LPG (Liquefied Petroleum Gas), is a well-known alternative fuel in the Czech Republic.
It is especially popular for its fundamentally lower price compared to petrol or diesel, given by a significantly lower excise tax, but its benefit is also in lower CO2 emissions per kilometer.
Like petrol and diesel, it also has its environmentally friendly variant - "bio LPG".
But it is quite a novelty - it first appeared on the European market two years ago and arrived in the Czech Republic a few days ago, according to a press release from the Czech LPG Association.
"These days, we have received the first fifteen tons of bio LPG, which will be distributed to our filling stations in a mixture with classic fossil LPG," the association quotes Jiří Karlík from Primagas.
However, bio LPG cannot be taken as bioethanol or biodiesel.
According to the association, it is chemically identical to conventional petroleum LPG, which many motorists now refuel their cars.
Therefore, it is also possible to mix both versions as desired.
"The only difference compared to conventional LPG is the method of production," says Ivan Indráček, chairman of the association, about bio LPG.
This is also one of the great advantages of bio LPG over other alternative fuels.
It is easy to transport and store, and the distribution infrastructure is also quite good, for example compared to hydrogen or electricity.
Currently, this gas is obtained as a by-product of the production of bioethanol from food residues and sugar cane.
In the future, it should also be produced in a targeted manner, e.g. from cellulosic biomass, i.e. wood waste.
On the other hand, conventional petroleum LPG is produced partly as a by-product of oil refining, partly by separation in natural gas extraction.
As a result, depending on the production technology and source, operating a bio LPG car is 40-70% more environmentally friendly in terms of carbon footprint than running on petroleum LPG and up to 90% compared to diesel.
However, it is not about CO2 emissions from the exhaust of the car, but about the ecology of fuel production, the so-called "well-to-tank" part.
Among the largest producers of bio LPG are currently petrochemical companies Eni, Total and Neste.
According to a recent update of the National Action Plan for Clean Mobility (NAP ČM), Unipetrol is also exploring the possibility of production in its Litvínov refinery.
According to the association's estimates, about 170,000 LPG vehicles run on LPG in the Czech Republic; The Ministry of the Environment states a slightly higher number in the NAP ČM, about 200 thousand.
According to statistics from the Ministry of Transport, almost 6,000 conversions of LPG cars were carried out last year alone.
It is possible to refuel with LPG in the Czech Republic at about 950 stations of various operators.
