An end to waste and churning out one collection after another.
Pietro Filipi abolishes discounts and bets on sustainability
Czech clothing brand Pietro Filipi wants to focus on sustainability and is embarking on a fundamental change in strategy.
He cancels discounts and no longer wants to churn out one collection after another.
The fact that the fashion industry is one of the biggest polluters of the environment is nothing new.
Billions of items of clothing end up in incinerators and landfills every year.
However, the view of slow fashion, often despised approach to dressing, has changed quite quickly in recent years.
Approximately half of Pietro Filipi's goods were sold at full price.
The other half, which was sold thanks to discounts, simply does not buy.
The company does not want to churn out one collection after another and at the end of each season to price products below their production price.
In addition, according to the owner Michal Mička, the times of new and old collections and blind following of rapidly changing fashion trends are gone.
"Most retailers count on discounts when buying goods, so a much higher margin is included in the full price.
So it's actually a bit of a scam," says Pietro Filipi owner Michal Mička.
In addition, the company wants to support local business with its approach.
"Each of our products is made of carefully selected quality fabrics and designed by local designers.
We emphasize that a large part of our collection is made up of so-called basic pieces - i.e. clothing that is timeless and over-season.
Worldwide, the premium brands segment is typical for the absence of any discounts, the price of the product simply corresponds to its quality and the discount is not needed," adds Mička.
