During the war, because of his Jewish origin, the Nazis dragged him to an internment camp, where he was held for several weeks.
However, thanks to the organization of Nicholas Winton, he and his brother managed to avoid a concentration camp.
In 1939, Taussig made it to the UK, where he volunteered for the Royal Air Force (RAF), and then underwent pilot training in Southern Rhodesia and Palestine.
He joined combat operations in early 1945.
After the Velvet Revolution, he visited the Czech Republic several times and his native Teplice, which granted him honorary citizenship.
Forty-six-year-old Kamil Vacek, known to people in the field of street graphic art under the nickname Camo, has been working with spray paints in the streets of Teplice for over 20 years.
