On Arctic Svalbard, a temperature record fell, they measured almost 22 degrees
"A 41-year-old record has been broken in Longyearbyen," the Norwegian Meteorological Institute said on Twitter.
By evening, the temperature there had risen to 21.7 degrees Celsius, beating the record set in 1979 by 0.4 degrees, he added.
Longyearbyen is the largest city on Svalbard, located about 1300 kilometers from the North Pole.
Svalbard is heating up faster than almost any other place on Earth.
This highlights the dangers posed by warming in other parts of the Arctic — from Alaska to Siberia, according to a report by the Norwegian Centre for Climate Studies last year.
According to him, the average temperature on Svalbard has increased by three to five degrees since the 70s of the 20th century.
By 2100, it may rise by as much as ten degrees if greenhouse gas emissions into the atmosphere are not reduced.
Rising temperatures in Svalbard can result in the melting of frozen soil, which threatens the stability of many buildings, roads and airports, and can cause more avalanches and landslides.
Climate warming also threatens Arctic fauna, such as polar bears and seals, which depend on the ocean ice sheet.
