The model of electricity purchase from Dukovany will be discussed by the government
On Monday, the government will discuss the model for purchasing electricity from the planned new unit of the Dukovany Nuclear Power Plant.
The bill assumes that if the purchase price is higher than the price of electricity on the market, all consumers will pay the difference through tariffs.
In the second case, when the purchase price is lower than the market price, the impact on consumers will be reversed.
Power electricity is an unregulated part of the final price of electricity for consumers.
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Industry Karel Havlíček (for ANO) and the energy company ČEZ have previously stated that the more likely scenario is that people will save on electricity thanks to the construction.
On the contrary, analysts point out that the long-term outlook for electricity prices on the markets is always uncertain, which developments in the past have shown several times.
The plan has previously been criticized by environmental groups.
"The feed-in tariff may be both below and above the market price of electricity.
Thus, the final impact at the time of applicability of the rule can be both negative and positive.
The impact will be distributed among customers according to the size of the circuit breaker - with lower consumption or according to electricity consumption - with higher electricity consumption," the Ministry of Industry and Trade (MPO) said in the documents accompanying the document.
Havlíček said in May that he expects the wholesale price of electricity to rise and that people will make money on the Dukovany construction.
Otherwise, the impact will be in tens of crowns per year per family, which, according to him, is far less than people pay annually in electricity bills to support so-called supported sources.
He had previously estimated that the purchase price could be between 50 and 60 euros (about 1320 to 1600 CZK) per megawatt hour (MWh).
The submitted material does not contain any proposal of the amount, it should be included in the purchase agreement.
The price of electricity on the Prague Energy Exchange for 2021, which is now the most stocked by traders, is currently around EUR 45 (about CZK 1190) per MWh.
"With the difference between the purchase price and the market price of electricity of ten euros, the surcharge for an average household with a consumption of 3.3 MWh per year could amount to less than CZK 100 per year," the Ministry of Industry and Trade wrote in documents for the government.
"We live in extremely turbulent times.
The coronavirus pandemic has shown us how vulnerable the global economy is.
For this reason, I consider the long-term prediction of market prices to be an explicitly speculative matter," Tomáš Voltr, executive director of the Energy Financial Group, previously told CTK.
The proposed law assumes that the purchase would be carried out by the Ministry of Industry and Trade, or a legal entity authorized by it owned by the state for a predetermined price.
The contract between the investor and the state, guaranteeing the conditions for the purchase of electricity, would be concluded for at least 30 years, with a possible extension of ten years, even repeated, but no longer than until the closure of low-carbon production.
The proposal defines a low-carbon generation facility as a nuclear reactor power generation facility connected to the grid with an installed capacity of at least 100 megawatts (MW) after 2030.
Havlíček previously said that the new Dukovany unit should have an output of 1200 MW and annually produce nine terawatt hours of electricity, which would correspond to a tenth of the expected Czech consumption.
The unit should be put into operation in 2036.
The financing model for the new Dukovany unit was approved by the government on Monday.
The state should finance the facility during construction interest-free, during operation it is expected to pay two percent interest.
The opposition disagrees with the financing model, and is also bothered by the possibility that Russian or Chinese companies would build Dukovany.
The state should participate in the construction by 70 percent.
The rest should be paid by ČEZ, which will also cover any additional costs.
ČEZ CEO Daniel Beneš told CTK in May that the expected sum for the construction of the unit at current prices is roughly six billion euros (approximately 162 billion crowns).
Contracts between the state and ČEZ on the construction of the new Dukovany unit will be signed on Tuesday.
