North America has been inhabited for 30,000 years, scientists say after tools found
Finds from the Chiquihuite Cave in the Mexican state of Zacatecas include 1930 tools made of limestone, including fine blades that may have been used to cut meat, and pointed objects that may have served as spear or spear points.
Scientists have found that the oldest of the tools date back to 33,000 to 31,000 years ago.
"There are only a few products of this age.
But they are there," said archaeologist Ciprian Ardelean of the University of Zacatecas and lead author of one of two studies published in the journal Nature.
The youngest tools are 12,500 years old.
According to experts, people inhabited the Chiquihuite Cave, located at a high altitude, for 20,000 years.
The hitherto generally accepted theory was that the first representatives of the species Homo sapiens crossed the land bridge from the area of today's Russia to Alaska about 13,500 years ago.
Archaeological evidence, including unique spearheads used to kill mammoths and other prehistoric animals, has shown that this Clovis culture subsequently spread throughout much of North America.
However, this model has been cracked in recent decades when several ancient settlements were discovered that were two to three thousand years older.
The second study, published in the journal Nature, reported 42 different sites across North America that showed human presence on the continent as early as 26,000 to 19,000 years ago.
Scientists believe that a small number of people may have arrived on the North American mainland earlier than previously thought.
Some of them could get to America by boat.
"It's clear that people were in America long before the development of the so-called Clovis culture," said anthropologist Ruth Gruhn of the University of Alberta in Canada.
