The air in homes is up to five times worse than outside.
Air fresheners and deodorants are harmful to health
Health is threatened not only by poor air quality outdoors, but also at home.
This was pointed out by Israeli human health expert Carol Abraham, as quoted by The Jerusalem Post.
Abraham, who was instrumental in creating Israel's Ministry of Environmental Protection, said household pollutants need to be addressed now, when many people are spending more time working from home.
Abraham mentioned research by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), according to which the quality of domestic air is up to five times worse than outdoor air.
The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that 3.8 million people die prematurely each year due to poor air quality in their homes.
"Due to the coronavirus epidemic, which has forced and continues to force many to work from home, people have had to spend more hours in their homes than before, so it's time to focus on indoor air quality," Abraham said.
In Israel, she says, almost no one cares about the quality of "domestic air."
Dangerous things that a person normally comes into contact with - paints, air fresheners, disinfectants, deodorants or pesticides - can be dangerous.
"The poisonous gas is also emitted by the clothes we regularly wear to the dry cleaners," Abraham said.
According to her, children, elderly household members and people with respiratory problems are most at risk.
Even otherwise healthy individuals may begin to suffer from problems such as headaches, fainting, nasal irritation, nosebleeds, vomiting or skin allergies.
With prolonged exposure to unhealthy substances, internal organs and the central nervous system can be damaged.
However, not all pollutants come from objects inside households, the source can also be the material from which the houses are built.
