Karel Gott did not like Václav Havel?!
Daughter Dominika revealed it
"Dad didn't have to do it for many years," she told Aha! Gott's eldest daughter, Dominika, said that the Master couldn't come up with Havel's name and whenever he was mentioned, Karel was always upset.
It's hard to say what they did to each other, but according to Dominica, the dispute began sometime in the mid-nineties.
"Dad said in an article after the revolution that it was easier for him than he was.
That Havel could have written in a drawer during the Dark Ages, but if he somehow resisted, his career would be over," says Gottová.
But then he adds that in the end, the Czech giants found their way to each other.
"I know that Havel could not have heard the word until his sixtieth birthday.
But then the president congratulated him with a letter on his birthday and suddenly my father's relationship with him began to change," Dominika recalls.
Ten years later, Gott even invited the former president to celebrate his seventieth birthday at the Ambassador Hotel on Wenceslas Square.
"And that's where a new era of their relationship began, because Dad then regularly invited Mr. Havel to his home at Bertramka," added the blonde, whose father died last October.
Slavík is also said to have regretted that he had never received a state award from Václav Havel.
After all, he got it in 2009, even though it was already from the hands of his successor in the post of Václav Klaus (79).
